===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|ぶた|yomi=k|alt=豕}}
{{wp|ja:ブタ}}
{{wp|Domestic pig}}

First attested in the mid-{{w|Muromachi period}}, some time in the late 1480s.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|豚・豕}}</ref>

Derivation ultimately {{unk|ja|nocap=1}}.

Some sources list possible theories:<ref>{{R:Gogen Yurai Jiten|ブタ／豚／ぶた|buta}}</ref><ref>{{m|ja||日本辞典|tr=Nihon Jiten|Japan Dictionary}}, entry for ''buta'' available online [http://www.nihonjiten.com/data/45943.html here] (in Japanese)</ref><ref>{{m|ja||由来・語源辞典|tr=Yurai / Gogen Jiten|Derivation / Etymology Dictionary}}, entry for ''buta'' available online [http://yain.jp/i/%E8%B1%9A here] (in Japanese)</ref>
* A shift from {{m|ja|太|tr=futo||[[fatty]] (fat individual), [[fatness]]}}
*: The vowel shift and voicing required to go from ''futo'' to ''buta'' seem problematic, considering Japanese sound shift patterns.
* Cognate with {{cog|ryu|ぶたさん|tr=butasan|t=fat}}.
* An [[onomatopoeia]] from the sound the animal makes, realized in Japanese as {{ja-r|ブー}}
*: The final ''-ta'' remains unexplained.
* Some combination of the two above
* A shift from {{m|ja|猪太|tr=ibuto||lit=swine + fatty}}
*: Attestable online, but not found in Japanese etymological resources. Difficult to judge provenance or timing.
* A borrowing from Korean or Mongolian
*: Neither Korean {{ko-l|돼지||pig}} nor {{cog|mn|гахай||pig}} show any phonological resemblance to ''buta'', ruling out these possibilities.

The word ''[[butakal]]'' appears in several languages of the Philippines with a sense of {{m|en|boar|pos=male pig}}, suggesting a possible source. However, any connection with an Austronesian language is only speculation.

The kanji is from {{der|ja|zh|豚||[[suckling]] [[pig]]}}. Compare {{cog|ja|猪|tr=inoshishi||[[boar]]}} from {{cog|zh|猪||pig}} and {{cog|ja|猿|tr=saru||[[monkey]]}} from {{cog|zh|猿||[[ape]]}}.

